Student Depression¶

Main Objective:¶

The purpose of this project is to build a predictive machine learning model that will predict who will get depressed.

We will be building our regression models using the dataset “Student Depression Dataset: Analyzing Mental Health Trends and Predictors Among Students”, created by Adil Shamim. The dataset, which is sourced from Kaggle.com, compiles a wide range of information about students in various cities across India.

Key Highlights of Dataset¶

  • Dataset Source: Student Depression Dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/adilshamim8/student-depression-dataset)

  • Dataset: There were 27901 records present. It was mostly complete, with only 3 missing values in the “Financial Stress” column.

  • Depression (Target Variable): This binary column shows if a student is experiencing depression (“0” = No and “1” = Yes).

  • Other Binary Variable: The “Have you ever had suicidal thoughts?” & “Family History of Mental Illness” consist of “Yes” and “No” string values.

Initial Patterns That Can Be Identified From The Data¶

After reviewing this dataset some patterns that can be identified from our numerical data include that Academic Pressure, Financial Stress, and work study hours all appear to have moderate positive correlations with depression meaning as academic pressure, financial stress and work study hours increase depression increases. At the same time age and study satisfaction also appear to have moderate-weaker correlations with depression, and this means as age and study satisfaction increase depression decreases. While on the other hand, work pressure and job satisfaction appear to have a very weak negative correlation with depression indicating almost no linear relationship with depression among these variables.¶
As well it appears when analyzing our categorical data that there was a balance among respondents of answers selected to categorical questions with the exception of profession where almost all respondents replied as student for there profession which is what would have been expected for this dataset. Another exception was noted in degree type where class of 12' was a strongly dominant response. Furthermore, it appears after analyzing the created bar graphs a majority of the respondents were male, had unhealthy dietary habits, slept less than 5 hours and had suicidal thoughts, among other items.¶

After reviewing the box plots above, we can see that several variables do not have any outliers and these variables include: Depression, Work/Study Hours, Study Satisfaction, and Academic Pressure. In the case of Depression the reason why it does not have any outliers is because it is binary in its collection through this study, while with the other variables it is likely the data is closely related, and follows a normal distribution.¶
There appears to be a few outliers with Job Satisfaction and Work Pressure above quartile 3, very few outliers below quartile 1 for CGPA, and a couple of outliers for Age above Quartile 3. What this would indicate is there are students in this study who feel they have great job Satisfaction or work Pressure, and a very small number of students who fall below the CGPA quartile 1 values, which is not much of a cause for concern and is reflective of a normal post secondary school environment. In the case of age what it does indiciate is while there are many students within Q1-Q3, there are a couple of mature students who are still pursuing higher education and this should not be a cause for concern either, as within any post secondary institution mature students are notably present. Overall, the outliers in the numerical dataset can be kept, given they are not a cause for concern and can be plausibly explained.¶

What Machine Learning Model Will Be Used And Why¶

After conducting our analysis and visualizing the data we will be using a supervised machine learning model and take a logisitic regression approcach when creating our machine learning model.¶
We have chosen to use supervised machine learning because our dataset has a known target that we are trying to best predict, which is depression. As well throughout this project we will be aiming to predict/classify data on its ability to predict student's risk of depression, and we will be providing our model clear training examples when creating it.¶
We have chosen to build a logistic regression model because we are trying to predict a binary outcome in this case as noted within our dataset which is whether a student is or is not depressed. Logistic regression is also useful for providing probability based outcomes ranging from 0-1, which aligns with how depression is noted within our dataset. In this case logistic regression will also help us to best understand how our categorical and numerical independent variables influences if a student is or is not depressed.¶

As indicated in the objective of this project we are aiming to identify the most effective key factors for predicting a student’s risk of depression based on demographic, social, financial, and academic indicators. Our key numerical variables that will be used to best understand this data are age, academic pressure, CGPA, study satisfaction, work/study hours, financial stress, work pressure, and job satisfaction. Our key categorical variables that will need to encoded during further data cleansing for use with this model include: gender, city, degree, sleep duration, dietary habits, have you ever had thoughts of suicide, family history of mental illness. This will need to be done for our categorical variables so they can be used with our proposed logistic regression model mentioned above.¶
Upon reviewing this dataset it does not appear to have any missing data after our initial data cleansing noted earlier. As well neither binary outcome of our target variable Depression appears to be heavily skewed in favour of one binary value or the other, and is proportionate to what one would reasonably expect in daily life, and there does not appear to be any duplicated entries. There will be a further deep dive review during our encoding and further data cleansing stage of this project, to verify this. As well during our data cleansing stage we will be removing any entries (32) that were not listed with the profession student as due to there professions they are outside of the scope of this project. Additionally, any changes or modifications to the data set will be noted and documented.¶
The outliers that have been discovered among our current numerical variables are not a cause for concern and should not be excluded, as noted earlier.¶
Finally, our current numerical variables do not appear to be normally distributed, however this is ok because a logistic regression model does not assume variables will be normally distributed.¶

Data Preparation and Preprocessing¶

As noted in part 1 when reviewing the data types, the 'Financial Stress' variable should be a 'float' data type instead of an 'object'. Preprocessing to convert 'Financial Stress' from an 'object' to a 'float' was completed. Afterwhich, missing values were addressed. See 'Part 1' for details

Converting Categorical Data¶

"Have you ever had suicidal thoughts ?" and "Family History of Mental Illness" were found to be binary feature with "Yes" & "No" values.
This is similar to the target variable "Depression", which has "0" and "1" as outcomes. Encoding these values into numerical data allows for developed models to learn from the relationship between these features and the target variable. Both features will be binary encoded, similar to the target variable.

No = "0" Yes = "1"

Assuming Ordinality for Sleep Duration and Dietary Habits¶

"Sleep Duration" & "Dietary Habits" are categorical features that can be converted into numerical data. Both variables are assumed to be ordinal. For example, "Unhealthy" is viewed as lower than "Moderate" in the "Dietary Habits" feature. Likewise, "7-8 hours" is viewed as higher than "5-6 hours" in the "Sleep Duration" feature.

In [91]:

Revised Correlation Analysis¶

In [103]:
plt.figure(figsize=(24, 16))
sns.heatmap(df.corr(numeric_only='true'), annot=True)
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap Matrix', fontsize=14)
plt.show()

Upon exploring the correlation matrix, it was determined numerical variables with a low correlation to the "Depression" target variable would be dropped. This included "Family History of Mental Illness", "Sleep Depression", "id", "Work Pressure", "CGPA", "Job Satisfaction", "Sleep Duration".

Also, it was determined "Age" would be dropped given depression can affect anyone at any stage in life. There are other underlying factors that may contribute to depression.

Lastly, "City", "Gender", "Degree", and "Profession" were not considered due to being categorical variables.

Data Modeling¶

We will be using a supervised machine learning model and be taking a logistic regression approach when creating our machine learning model. We selected this approach because our dataset has a known target variable (depression) that we are trying to best predict. As well throughout this project we will be providing our model clear training examples when creating it.

A logistic regression model was chosen because we are trying to predict a binary outcome which in this case is whether a student is or is not depressed. Logistic regression is also useful for providing probability outcomes ranging from 0-1, which aligns with the binary nature of depression in this dataset.

In order to test the accuracy of the model, we will create a Random Forest classifier model for comparison. This classfication model can also be used to predict a binary outcome with a known target variable.
